INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '714acde4-7dfe-4755-91f1-cc3ff3979967',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Kafka Dead Letter Queues — Poison Message Handling and Backoff Retry$escape$,
  $escape$Kafka has no native DLQ, so you build one. When a consumer fails to process a message, the naive approach is to `seek` back and retry in a tight loop — this blocks the partition and starves other consumers. The production pattern: use a retry topic chain (`topic.retry-1`, `topic.retry-2`, `topic.dlq`) with exponential backoff encoded as a header.

Publish the failed record to `topic.retry-1` with a `retry-count` and `next-process-after` header (epoch ms). A separate consumer group polls the retry topic but skips records where `next-process-after > System.currentTimeMillis()`, calling `consumer.pause()` + `consumer.seek()` to hold position without spinning. After max retries (e.g. 3), route to the DLQ topic.

Spring Kafka's `DefaultErrorHandler` with `ExponentialBackOffWithMaxRetries` automates this via `SeekToCurrentErrorHandler` under the hood, wiring retry topics through `DeadLetterPublishingRecoverer`. For non-Spring consumers, implement `ConsumerRebalanceListener` to replay DLQ messages on demand — never auto-consume the DLQ, treat it as an audit log first.$escape$,
  $escape$@Bean
public DefaultErrorHandler errorHandler(KafkaTemplate<Object, Object> template) {
    var recoverer = new DeadLetterPublishingRecoverer(template,
        (rec, ex) -> new TopicPartition(rec.topic() + ".dlq", rec.partition()));

    var backoff = new ExponentialBackOffWithMaxRetries(3);
    backoff.setInitialInterval(1_000L);
    backoff.setMultiplier(2.0);
    backoff.setMaxInterval(10_000L);

    return new DefaultErrorHandler(recoverer, backoff);
}$escape$,
  $escape$kotlin$escape$,
