INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e6fd61ce-cd7f-46a3-bc42-1e6cf5de9bf4',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Kafka Idempotent Consumers — Safely Handling Duplicate Messages$escape$,
  $escape$Kafka's at-least-once delivery guarantee means your consumer will occasionally process the same message twice — during rebalances, broker failovers, or after a crash before offsets are committed. The safest pattern is to make your processing logic idempotent at the storage layer, not just in memory.

Use the message's topic + partition + offset as a natural idempotency key. Before processing, check a deduplication store (Redis with a short TTL, or a `processed_offsets` Postgres table) for that key. If present, skip and commit. If absent, process and record atomically.

For exactly-once semantics within Kafka itself, enable the transactional API: set `enable.idempotence=true` and `transactional.id` on the producer, then use `beginTransaction()` / `sendOffsetsToTransaction()` / `commitTransaction()` to atomically write output records and commit input offsets in a single transaction. This prevents zombie producers from re-emitting during leader epoch changes.

Avoid relying on `auto.offset.reset=earliest` as a safety net — it's a recovery knob, not an idempotency strategy. Always pair offset management with a durable dedup check.$escape$,
  $escape$producer.initTransactions();
try {
  producer.beginTransaction();
  producer.send(new ProducerRecord<>("output-topic", key, value));
  producer.sendOffsetsToTransaction(
    Map.of(new TopicPartition(record.topic(), record.partition()),
      new OffsetAndMetadata(record.offset() + 1)),
    consumer.groupMetadata()
  );
  producer.commitTransaction();
} catch (ProducerFencedException e) {
  producer.close(); // zombie producer — another instance took over
} catch (KafkaException e) {
  producer.abortTransaction();
}$escape$,
  $escape$java$escape$,
